# Complete Git + GitHub Setup Notes (Mac M4)

## Project Structure Example

```text
htdocs/
├── D/
│   ├── Demo/
│   └── school_software_v1/
```

* `htdocs` = XAMPP root folder
* `D` = parent folder containing both projects
* `Demo` and `school_software_v1` = actual projects

---

# 1. Open Terminal on Mac

### Method 1

Press:

```text
Command + Space
```

Type:

```text
Terminal
```

Press Enter.

---

# 2. Go to Project Folder

## Upload only Demo project

```bash
cd /Applications/XAMPP/xamppfiles/htdocs/Demo
```

## Upload only school_software_v1 project

```bash
cd /Applications/XAMPP/xamppfiles/htdocs/school_software_v1
```

## Upload both projects together

```bash
cd /Applications/XAMPP/xamppfiles/htdocs/D
```

---

# 3. Check Current Folder

```bash
pwd
```

---

# 4. Check Files

```bash
ls
```

---

# 5. Remove Old Git History

(Removes previous Git history and large SQL file history)

```bash
rm -rf .git
```

---

# 6. Initialize New Git Repository

```bash
git init
```

---

# 7. Create .gitignore File

(Prevents SQL files and Mac files from uploading)

```bash
echo "u851190831_eps.sql" > .gitignore
```

Add Mac system files:

```bash
echo ".DS_Store" >> .gitignore
```

View .gitignore:

```bash
cat .gitignore
```

---

# 8. Add Files to Git

```bash
git add .
```

---

# 9. Check Git Status

```bash
git status
```

---

# 10. Commit Files

```bash
git commit -m "Fresh upload"
```

---

# 11. Rename Branch to main

```bash
git branch -M main
```

---

# 12. Connect GitHub Repository

```bash
git remote add origin git@github.com:morphozblue-sys/Morphozblue.git
```

Check remote:

```bash
git remote -v
```

---

# 13. Push Project to GitHub

## Normal push

```bash
git push -u origin main
```

## Force push

(Overwrites GitHub repo with local files)

```bash
git push -u origin main --force
```

---

# 14. SSH Key Setup

## Generate SSH key

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "morphozblue@gmail.com"
```

Press Enter 3 times.

---

## Start SSH agent

```bash
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
```

---

## Add SSH key

```bash
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
```

---

## Show SSH public key

```bash
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
```

Copy output and add here:

GitHub → Settings → SSH and GPG keys

---

## Test SSH connection

```bash
ssh -T git@github.com
```

Expected output:

```text
Hi username! You've successfully authenticated
```

---

# 15. Fix Large SQL File Error

## Remove SQL file from Git tracking

```bash
git rm --cached u851190831_eps.sql
```

---

## Ignore SQL file permanently

```bash
echo "u851190831_eps.sql" >> .gitignore
```

---

## Commit changes

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Ignore SQL backup file"
```

---

# 16. Create Folder in Git

Git does not track empty folders.

## Create folder

```bash
mkdir uploads
```

## Add placeholder file

```bash
touch uploads/.gitkeep
```

## Commit

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Added uploads folder"
git push
```

---

# 17. Delete File From Git

## Delete file locally

```bash
rm filename
```

Example:

```bash
rm main.php
```

---

## Commit deletion

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Deleted file"
git push
```

---

# 18. Delete Folder

```bash
rm -rf foldername
```

Example:

```bash
rm -rf uploads
```

---

# 19. Remove Git Submodule Issue

If GitHub shows a folder with an arrow icon, it means it became a submodule.

## Remove submodule tracking

```bash
git rm --cached Demo
```

---

## Remove submodule metadata

```bash
rm -rf .git/modules/Demo
```

---

## Remove .gitmodules file

```bash
rm -f .gitmodules
```

---

## Add folder again as normal folder

```bash
git add Demo
```

---

## Commit changes

```bash
git commit -m "Convert Demo from submodule to normal folder"
```

---

## Push changes

```bash
git push origin main --force
```

---

# 20. Pull Latest Changes

```bash
git pull origin main --no-rebase --allow-unrelated-histories
```

---

# 21. Open Current Folder in Finder

```bash
open .
```

---

# 22. Open VS Code in Current Folder

```bash
code .
```

---

# 23. Delete Entire GitHub Repository

1. Open repository on GitHub
2. Go to Settings
3. Scroll to Danger Zone
4. Click:

```text
Delete this repository
```

5. Type repository name to confirm.

---

# 24. Common Git Commands

## Check status

```bash
git status
```

## Add all files

```bash
git add .
```

## Commit changes

```bash
git commit -m "message"
```

## Push changes

```bash
git push
```

## Pull changes

```bash
git pull
```

## Check branches

```bash
git branch
```

## Check remotes

```bash
git remote -v
```

---

# 25. Important Notes

* Run Git commands from the correct project folder.
* Running Git inside `htdocs` uploads everything inside it.
* Running Git inside `Demo` uploads only Demo project.
* `.gitignore` prevents unwanted files from uploading.
* `--force` overwrites GitHub repository contents.
* Git does not upload empty folders unless they contain files.
